properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Brief, intense snowfall is expected. Visibilities will be rapidly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow. A brief but intense snow squall associated with a strong cold front will cross portions of far northern Ontario today. As of 11 AM CST, the front extends from roughly Sachigo Lake to Sandy Lake. The snow squall is expected to intensify as it heads eastward. It should reach places like Big Trout Lake, Kasabonika and Kingfisher Lake later this afternoon. Northwest winds gusting to 70 km/h combined with heavy snow during the passage of the front will likely result in a brief period of very poor visibility and whiteout conditions. A general snowfall accumulation of 4 to 8 cm is possible. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard possible Saturday. A strong low pressure system will make its way through Hudson Bay toward southern Baffin Island on Friday. Heavy snow is expected to begin late Friday or early Saturday along with rapidly intensifying easterly winds. Current indications are for up to 10 cm of fresh snow accompanied at times with winds gusting to 80 km/h. At minimum, visibility reductions in blowing snow are expected for much of Saturday. Blizzard conditions will also be possible should the system continue on its current forecast track or intensify further. Conditions will improve late Saturday as the system moves off into Foxe Basin. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility due to blowing snow is expected this afternoon and evening. Heavy snow and strong westerly winds with gusts of 70 to 80 km/h will affect the region beginning late this afternoon as an intense cold front moves east across northern Ontario today and tonight. The heavy snow and strong winds occurring together will result in blowing snow that will significantly reduce visibilities late this afternoon and this evening. As the cold front moves east, the heavy snow will taper to flurries late in the evening, however the winds will remain strong and could continue to whip up the freshly fallen snow. Conditions are expected to improve early Saturday morning as the winds diminish. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for tonight. A narrow but possibly intense snow squall band, associated with the passage of a cold front, will move across northeastern Ontario tonight. This linear snow squall band will extend from Attawapiskat southwest to Armstrong this evening and is expected to move eastward throughout the night. By midnight, the snow squall band will extend from Fort Albany southwest to Nakina and will begin to weaken as it continues eastward. A snowfall accumulation of 4 to 8 cm is possible with this snow squall. Strong winds with gusts of up to 60 km/h are also possible with the passage of the cold front tonight. These winds are expected to ease Friday overnight. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will accumulate quickly. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to the reduced visibility. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

A strong low pressure system is making its way through Hudson Bay toward southern Baffin Island. At Iqaluit, snow will begin Saturday morning along with rapidly intensifying easterly winds. With winds gusting up to 80 km/h, a blizzard will develop in the morning and continue throughout the day. Conditions will improve in the evening as the system moves off into Foxe Basin. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for tonight. A narrow but possibly intense snow squall band, associated with the passage of a cold front, will move across northeastern Ontario tonight. This linear snow squall band will extend from Attawapiskat southwest to Armstrong this evening and is expected to move eastward throughout the night. By midnight, the snow squall band will extend from Fort Albany southwest to Nakina and will begin to weaken as it continues eastward. A snowfall accumulation of 4 to 8 cm is possible with this snow squall. Strong winds with gusts of up to 60 km/h are also possible with the passage of the cold front tonight. These winds are expected to ease Friday overnight. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will accumulate quickly. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to the reduced visibility. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected to develop. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. A cold front moving across northern Ontario today will bring southerly winds over lake Superior ahead of the front that may generate lake effect snow squalls. These snow squalls are expected to develop late this afternoon or this evening in an area stretching from Marathon east to Wawa and south to Agawa. Heavy bursts of snow and significantly reduced visibilities at times can be expected late this afternoon and tonight. Travel along Highway 17 during this time may be hazardous. A total snowfall accumulation of 10 to 15 cm is possible by Saturday morning. Areas closer the lake shore where the temperature is slightly above the freezing mark may accumulate less snow than areas further inland. The snow squalls will begin to weaken near midnight for Marathon and Wawa and by Saturday morning for Agawa. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Brief, intense snowfall is expected. Visibilities will be rapidly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow. A brief but intense snow squall associated with a strong cold front will cross portions of far northern Ontario today. As of 3:30 PM EST (2:30 PM CST), the front has passed areas such as Sachigo Lake and Muskrat Dam. The snow squall is expected to intensify as it heads eastward. It should reach places like Big Trout Lake, Kasabonika and Kingfisher Lake later this afternoon and reach the northern Webequie region by early evening. Northwest winds gusting to 70 km/h combined with heavy snow during the passage of the front will likely result in a brief period of very poor visibility and whiteout conditions. A general snowfall accumulation of 4 to 8 cm is possible. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
